04322nam a22005415i 9780226764597DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20092008ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802267645977 a10.7208/97802267645972doi  a(DE-B1597)523119  a(OCoLC)1135576779  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aDT433.545.T34bS65 2008 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a305.896/395a305.896395a306.41 aSmith, James Howard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBewitching Development :bWitchcraft and the Reinvention of Development in Neoliberal Kenya /cJames Howard Smith. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2009] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b5 halftones, 3 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChicago Studies in Practices of Meaning00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface. Escaping Development -- tChapter 1. Bewitching Development: The Disintegration and Reinvention of Development in Kenya -- tChapter 2. I Still Exist! Taita Historicity -- tChapter 3. Development’s Other: Witchcraft as Development through the Looking Glass -- tChapter 4. “Each Household Is a Kingdom”: Development and Witchcraft at Home -- tChapter 5. “Dot Com Will Die Seriously!” Spatiotemporal Miscommunication and Competing Sovereignties in Taita Thought and Ritual -- tChapter 6. NGOs, Gender, and the Sovereign Child -- tChapter 7. Democracy Victorious: Exorcising Witchcraft from Development -- tChapter 8. Conclusion: Tempopolitics, Or Why Development Should Not Be Defined as the Improvement of Living Standards -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThese days, development inspires scant trust in the West. For critics who condemn centralized efforts to plan African societies as latter day imperialism, such plans too closely reflect their roots in colonial rule and neoliberal economics. But proponents of this pessimistic view often ignore how significant this concept has become for Africans themselves. In Bewitching Development, James Howard Smith presents a close ethnographic account of how people in the Taita Hills of Kenya have appropriated and made sense of development thought and practice, focusing on the complex ways that development connects with changing understandings of witchcraft. Similar to magic, development’s promise of a better world elicits both hope and suspicion from Wataita. Smith shows that the unforeseen changes wrought by development—greater wealth for some, dashed hopes for many more—foster moral debates that Taita people express in occult terms. By carefully chronicling the beliefs and actions of this diverse community—from frustrated youths to nostalgic seniors, duplicitous preachers to thought-provoking witch doctors—BewitchingDevelopment vividly depicts the social life of formerly foreign ideas and practices in postcolonial Africa.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEconomic developmentzKenyazTaita Hills. 0aTaita (African people)xRites and ceremonies. 0aTaita (African people)xSocial life and customs. 0aWitchcraftzKenyazTaita Hills. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226764597423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226764597.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles